{"/service/ndnp/vtu/batch_vtu_fennal_ver01/data/sn91066782/00415627968/1920123101/0611.xml":{"full_text":"'HE BARRE DAILY TIMES, BARRE, VT., FR1UAY. DKCKMHKK 31, mil.\n'4\nBARRE DAILY TIME9\nFRIDAY, DECEMBER 31, 1920.\nPubllKhod Evr W-k-DT Afternoon f\nTHE BAKKtf DAILY TIMES. INC.\nFrank E. Lnglcr..PubHhtf\nEntered t tbt Pan tome t Bsrrs M soon.\nClass Mail MattT\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nOne yer b msil JJ\nThrw mrttths by mail .V\nOn. month by mail\nSlncle copy\nAll tubicriptioM caih In adwnca.\nMEMBER OK 1HK A880CIATKH PRBS\nTh AmUlid Prrt la xc1lvly entitles\nI lb in for rnubHtUen iw\npilrhn ertditd to H r not thtrwlae er\niud In Ihl. paper, aa4 alt the local M\nSsblUhfd thoraia.\nThe now year holds something bettor\nin store.\nSugar i retailing so low that pco-\npie are almost forgetting that it eve\nwent soaring into the gold coin cla8.\nThe business of cabinet-making is\none of the overworked industries at\nthe present time. It is the cabinet\nwhich will be set up in Washington,\nD. C.\nThings have come to a pretty pass\nwhen the police commissioner of Hack\nensack, X. J., can't go about his busi\nness without being held up by foot\npads, i\nWe notice a Burlington merchant is\nadvertising \"skating .boots for ladies\nmade of heavy oil-tanned leather.\" We\nhad no-idea Burlington ladies were so\ntough as that.\nThe casualties in New York City\nduring the past six months of crime\nwould amount to a good-sized hattle\nrecord were they to be brought togeth\ner. It is a most bloody record indeed.\nPresident Wilson has rejected an of-\nIfer of $1 30,000 for a literary work, (in\nthe ground that the amount is too\nI large. Wilson must be afflicted with a\nI disease new and mysterious among\nAmericans.\nThe retail price of milk is to be re\nduced at once in Winooski from 15 to\n13 cents per quart on account of the\nI reduction in t\"he price of feeds. This\nrelief will help out many Winooski\nfamilies which Jiave been hard put to\nit since the closing of some of the\nmills located there.\nYes, we're all glad to\ngive a swift kick to\nthe o'd year with his\nhigh prices.\nNow's the time to\nmake your dollar bring\nhome its old time value.\nSuits for men, the\nquality that has been\nsold 'from $60 to $70\nnow at $40 to $50.\nOvercoats, the class that\nwas priced $75 to $100\nnow $50 to $65.\nAND for Boys, Cloth\ning the prices have\nreached the bottom.\nF. H.Rogers\nCompany\nSUNDAY SERVICES\nAT THE CHURCHES\nTimes and Places of Worship\nand Subjects of Sermons.\nA FAVORED LOOK.\nThe calendar year coming to a ch)3e\nhas been a disastrous one in many re\nspects for the entire country, and also\nof the whole world. The close of the\nWorld war found the nations greatly\nIweakened in vitality through the pro-\nItractcd and wearing struggle; and it\nI found the people relaxed from the ten\nsion of war to such an extent that\nI they fell into loose habits of (thinking\nand acting. There was more or less\ndisorganization throughout the world.\nThat the United States shared in the\nIgeneral trend of the times goes with\nout saying. This country of ours;\njustly famed for its stability of pur\npose, was somewhat shaken from its\nnormal poise. A great unrest stirred\nthe people of the nation, particularly\nthose who were wage-earners. Trices\nof commodities were high; and there\nwas an insistent clamor after more\nwages with which to meet the cost of\nliving. In some instances the wages\nwent up: and in most instances the\n1 prices of commodities stayed up du.'ing\nthe early part of the year. Then Came\nla period when production started to\ncatch up with the demand; yet the\nexpected fall in prices did not devel\nop. This greatly stirred the uncst\nf the people; and there grew jp a\nrebellion against purchase of sny ex\ncept the bare necessities of life. Or\nders to the mills and factories were\nreduced or cancelled entirely. I'll 'is\ndeprived of orders the mills and fac\ntories were forced to shut down, mil\nlions of people being thrown out of\nemployment for the time-being. Such\nlis the situation in the United States\ni in the last day of the calendar year.\nHowever, the situation in not so dark\nus it seems to be. Here is a nation of\nL.Tet natural resources, of tremendous\ni igor and markedly progressive. It\nisn't star down. Moreover, there are\nhure indications that the country is\nDing about the problems of readjtrst-\nnent incident to peace-after-war in\na manner as to make possible the\nreturn of prosperity. The law of sup\nply and demand is coming into pMy;\nprior and wages are adjusting them\nselves under that law. The mills and\nfactories are still running at low ra-\nk-acity or are even idle. But it will\nhot be f.ir long. The supply is being\np toauoted, the demand will hevm\ni-tronger. Soon tha operations will\nI,t to start to make a supply to\nUwt the demand oa fairly even bel\nnee. Then the normal order will be\nrioreL That this retoratinn ill\nme during the calendar year ifMI\nI rem certain. So let s Uae a more\nIVerful attitude.\nEsiINDIGESTION\nm\nm\nQUICK RELIEF!\nPrtc. 2S-50-7S\nlo m t Pier rota\ntuec srr cor s sevsi\nHAKtSt Of\n8COTTS EMULSION\nGrowth Through Confidence\nPublic confidence is this bank's most valuable asset.\nWhile it is an intangible asset, not carried on the books, with\nout it, the tangible listed assets, would, indeed be small in amount\nand of little value.\nPublic confidence is the great fundamental asset upon which the\nsecurity of the bank rests; it is sometimes called \"good will\" and\nthis item of \"good will\" is also the bank's greatest direct source of\nincome. No bank can grow unless the public believe in it, its own\ncustomers must not only have full confidence in the ability and\nintegrity of its management but they should show this confi\ndence by boosting it whenever possible.\nFurther than this, the bank must conduct its affairs so that\nthere shall be formed an increasing volume of favorable senti\nment among all classes of people who may come in contact with\nthe bank in any way whatsoever.\nThe increasing degree of public confidence which this bank\ncommands is, perhaps, best reflected by its growth in deposits.\nThe following figures indicate the increase in number of ac\ncounts and amount of such increase for the year 1920.\nNew Savings Accounts since January 1, 1920 1231\nIncrease in Savings Department since January 1, 1920, $403,465.00\nThe Peoples National Bank\nDeposits made or or before January 13th will draw interest\nfrom January 1 at 4 per cent.\nOFFICERS\nF. D LADD, President W. C. JOHNSON, JR., Cashier\nVV. M. HOLDEN, Vice-President F. K. BEARD, Asst. Cashier\nWashington Baptist Church Samuel\nMead, pastor. Service at 3 p. m.\nSpiritualist Society Kev. F.ffie I.\nWebster will preach to-morrow in tie\nWorthen hall at 2:30 and 7 P- AH\nwelcome.\nSt. John the Baptist Episcopal\nChurch, Websterville Duvid C. Hunt\nington, rector. 2 p. m., hunday school.\n3 p. m., services and sermon. All welcome.\nChurch of Jesus Christ of Latter Day\nSaints Services are being held in the\nWorthen block every Sunday. .Sunday\nservices, 10 to 11 a. m., tveryoouy\nwelcome.\nBrook Street Italian Baptist Mis\nsionBert .1. Lehigh, superintendent.\nBible school at 3 o clock on huuday.\nAll children of the community are\nurged to be present\nWebsterville Bantist Church Samuel\nMead, pastor. Morning service at 10:30. J\nEvening service at 7 o clock. JHiQweeK\nmeeting Thursday evening at 7 o'clock.\nServices are to be held regularly.\nChurch of tha Good Shepherd Da\nvid C. Huntington, rector. 8 a. m.,\nholy communion. 10:30 a. m.. Bervice\nand sermon on \"The Virgin Birth of\nChrist.\" 12 m., Sunday school. Public\ninvited.\nChristian Science Church Service at\n10:45 a. m. Sunday. Sunday school at\n12 m. Wednesday evening service at\n7:30. 'Reading room open on Tuesday,\nThursday and Saturday from 3 to 5.\n7 Summer street.\nFirst Presbyterian Church W. MoN\nKittredge, pastor. Morning worship\nat 10:30, with talk to the children and\nNew Year' sermon to adults. Bible\nschool at 12 m. Kvening worship at\n7. Monday, 7 p. m., the boy ycout\nmeet in t tic vestry. Thursday, 7:30\np. m., prayer meeting. A cordial wel\ncome is extended to the public to wor\nship with us. Why not begin the\nXew Year right by attending church\nsomewhere f\nHeading Methodist Episcopal Church\nBailey (ts.tr.prt l.ipsky, pastor. Morn\ning service, 10:3; sermon theme. \"Life\nfor .Testis' Sake.\" Kvening service at\n7, illustrated lecture, \"How Some So\ncialistic Colonics Have AVorked.\" Come\nwith us and face the facts. You may\nk relevant questions at the close of\nthis lecture. Sunday school at 11:45.\nFnworth league at ll. Prayer service\nThursday at 7:30 p. m. Boy scout.\nFriday, :30 p. m.\nEast Bsrre Confregstional Church\nTames Ramage, pastor. Morning serv.\nice at 10:30. A New Year's sermon\nwill be preached bv the pastor. Church\nehool at 11:45. Christian Endeavor\nservice at T p. m. Mr. Kamage wishes\nto thank the church and community\nfor the recent shower of good things\nthey gave him, alo for their ecnron\nmoney gift at Christmas. He would\nalso thank all for their remembrance\nrf Mr. Pamee in her sickness. The\nunfsil ne. enerii, characteristic kind-\nm of Eat Bsrre people would be\nhard to beat.\nFirst Baptist Church Bert .T. I.e\nI'h. pator. TH rtr will preach\nn Sundar at 10 SO and 7 o'clnk.\nMnrnin s'ubit. \"Christian Fidelity.\"\nKrening sulijert, \"Kwpiti the H-art.\"\nBible hoo at II oVlnck. Yonn?\np-opU's inert inf at I'rsyer mtt-H-e\nThnrdsr evening at 7:30. Kvcrv-\non given a rc.rdisl invitation n wur- j\nh!p with n at all service r.f the\nrfcurrh. Tomorrow (Saturday 'be\nannual sneetln? of the rhurh wdl be j\nheld. Sei..n opens at 2 V1k. Sup\nper will be wrved free at .V3n In ell'\nmember snd adherer.!\" .f the rbq-rli\nIt i earnestly re.)ei,f tht evr\nmetr.Vr arij all interred 1 pre\ner,t\nCo!rett'cl Charcb F. U\npeed. D. P.. fatw. 10 W. enirt ng\nwr-n p: I rwf erw\" and '-tn-i!\nf tSe Ior' sufpet. 12 an, P. t\nebnf.l. J Fi n'':np \"f tHe i jn-..r\na. p. r.g .f V. V. V C. 1.\nt p. W.-. l---iM.f JtnT'hp tii p--s- i tg\nIt the ptnr; inkwt, Tt Year\nA1\" Hmi ft the sx year.\nF. D. Ladd\nC. VV.\nVV. M.\nAverill\nDIRECTORS\nHolden VV. D. Smith A. J. Young\nF. L. Sargent VV. C. Johnson, Jr.\nHave You Joined Our\n1921\nChristmas-Thrift Club?\nIF NOT, JOIN TO-DAY\nAre you one of the hundreds of happy people whose names are\nenrolled in our\nChristmas -Thrift Club\nDon't let this golden opportunity pass by but MAKE YOUR\nSTART NOW.\nDeposit something, even though it be a 'small beginning, and\nyour first step will be taken on the ladder of SUCCESS.\nJoining is very simple, just bring or send the first week's pay\nment, either twenty-five cents, fifty cents, one dollar, two dollars\nor five dollars. Your messenger will be given an account deposit\nbook in your name showing the amount paid. Anyone can join\nby mail, and your membership book will be sent by return mail.\nOUARRY SAVINGS BANK\nAND TRUST CO.\nBarre, Vermont.\nBEN A. EASTMAN, President\nIT .T f JONES Vice-President.\nC. M. WILLEY, Treasurer.\nDIRECTORS\nBen A Eastman James M. BoutweU W. O. Reynolds H. F. Cutler E. L. Scott\nH J. M. Jones. B. W. Hooker H. H. Jackson\nl i B;\nTuesday, 3 p. m., meeting of the Fa\nhola rampfire girls.\" 8:30 p. ra., meet\ning of tle hoy scouts. Wednesday,\n2:30 p. m., meeting of th woman's as\nsociation. 6:13 p. m., meeting of the\nWillheka campfire girls. Thursday,\n7:30 p. ni.', midweek service of song\nand prayer. The public is invited to\nall services.\nFirst tniversalist Church Frank O.\nHokerk, pastor. Sunday services: Pi\nvine worship at 10:30 a. m.; sermon\nsubject, \"The New Year.\" Miss Brown\nwill sing. Sunday school at 1 1 45 a.\nm. Junior league at 4 p. m. There\nwill be no evening service. The an\nnual meeting of the .church will 1\nheld on Monday, Jan. 3. Supper will\nbe served at C p. m. and this will be\nfollowed by the business session at\n7:30 o'clock. Flection of ollicers, re\nports of officers and the auxiliary so\ncieties. Every I'nivcrsalist is invited\nto be present. The report this year\nwill prove to be an inspiration and the\ncats will be of the usual standard of\nexcellence. The divine science class\non Wednesday at 7:30 p. m. Choir re\nhearsal on Thursday at 7 p. m. Com\nmencing next Sunday, ,T;in. 2, Miss\nBetty Brown of Goddard will be the\nchoir director and have full charge of\nthe choir and its activities. Miss Mary\nlase has been hired as organist. The\npastor suueests thnt every Universal\nist make the one New Year resolution\nthat they will attend church and he\nhopes to-see you all in church on the\nfirt Sunday in the new year, 1021.\nWhat a glorious celebration it would\nbe and at any rate he wishes you all a\nright happy New Year.\nTALK OF THE TOWN\nA leading hairdresser says she has\nfound nothing aa good as Parisian\nRage to cure dandruff and make the\nhair wavy, thick and lustrous. E. A.\nI)rown sells the genuine. adv.\nEat what you want. Sleep with peace\nand tranquillity. Reflnin your lost vig\nor and nerve force. Bitro-Phosphate is\npurposed to give you added weight and\nstrength, and to make you well. Ob\ntainable at E. A. Drown Co.'s drug\nstore. Strictly guaranteed.\nDon't forizct that we make a spe\ncialty of dyeing old clothes to look\nlike new at \"little cost. Why not dou\nble the wear of your clothes! Barre\nCleaning. Dyeing' Tailoring Shop.\n1S2 North Main street, Barre. Walter\nKrinovitz, Prop., 'phone 102 J.\nEAST BARRE\nWEBSTERVILLE\nMr. and Mrs. Robert Mitchell of\nWebsterville received word Wednesday\nof the death of their grandson, George\nWilliam Anderson, oldest child of Mr.\nand Mrs. William Anderson, ffanna, Al.\nberta. The deceased was burn in Web\nsterville Feb. 22, 1010, and at the age\nof one year moved wkh his parents to\nAlberta, where his father Is engaged in\nwheat farming. Besides his parents, he\nleaves to mourn his loss two brothers\nand one sister, Robert, John and Mar\ngaret, also grandparents in Scotland,\na well as those here, and a great\ngrandparent, Mrs. Jane Jamieson, now\nvisiting in Scotland.\nA\nT\nI\nO\nN\nTHE emumitl SCHOOL\naiasnv,\nY\nM\nN\nT\nThey'll Give You Real Wear\nBoth these \"Ball-Band\" Rubber\nShoes have leather tops. The\nribbed foot of the smaller shoe is\nheavy gum. The rubber foot of\nthe higher shoe is reinforced with\nheavy duck.\nCome in and let us show you these\nstrongly made, long-wearing shoes.\nYou'll find any other Rubber Foot\nwear you may need in our com\nplete \"Ball-Band\" stock.\nThere will be a service in the Congre\ngational church Friday evening to\nwatch the old year out and the new\nyear in. There will be a swia! time\nwih refreshments from 0 to 11. At 11\no'clock a service of prayer and praise\nwill bo held. All, especially the young,\nare invited.\nSPECIAL SALE FOR\nNEW YEAR'S DAY\nWith each three pounds of Our Sp\ncial Coffee at 99c we will jive\npound FREE.\nExtra (food Brwm, each\nSun Maid Seeded Raisins, pkg.\nSuccotash, can\nHIGHEST QUALITY\nLOWEST PRICES\nA New lot of Fancy Walnut\nMeats just arrived, spe- 1\ncial, per lb 59c\nMolasses Kisses, per lb. .30c\n50c Value Chocolate, lb 30c\nIndian River Florida Oranges\nCalifornia Sunkist Navels,\ndoz, 25c, 30c, 35c, 40c, 50c, 60c\nGrapefruit, 3 and 2 for 25c\nBananas, doz 30c, 40c, 50c\non' Grapes, per lb 35c\nI New Nuts of all kinds, Zoc, up\n60e Fancy Fips, lb 20c, up\n25c T v- a r- in. i\"w\nfor'!!!.'! 25c Good Juicy Dates lb 22c\n22c, Imported .Malaga Cluster\n9ci Raisins, package 48c\n,i Fresh Roasted Peanuts 2\n22c quarts for 25c\n59c' Home-made Salted Peanuts\ni per lb 30c\n2 Pop Corn. 3 lbs for 25c\n3 IDS ivr .UC\nears, Apples\nFor Your Old\nHot\nWater\nBottle\nCorn can 15c;\nOur Bet Salt Pork, per lb\nWorcester Salt, per bag\nTea Beans, per lb\n(iood Head Rice, per lb\nI'earl Tapioca. 3 lb. for\nWathinglon Creamery Butter, lb.\nArmour's Tork Sausage, in 2 lb.\ni bags, each\nsmoked shoulder., per ih 24c! It